{"key":"processedPost-19846348","value":{"id":19846348,"first":19844138,"last":19847392,"when":1397534640,"utime":"04/15/14 07:04 AM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>Mr. Alien said:</strong><br />So when you inoculate with spore solution, the first day that germinate starts as linear myc? Then in a matter of hours they become ropey myc, i am just guessing..<br /><blockquote>Quote:<br /><b><i>RogerRabbit said:</i></b><br />You're both wrong.</blockquote><br />Hey RR can you explain? or point out where i am wrong? <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/rolleyes.gif\" alt=\":rolleyes:\" title=\":rolleyes:\"/></blockquote><br />Spores germinate into hyphae.&nbsp; They're not linear or rhizomorphic.&nbsp; Hyphae have lots of branches like mold.&nbsp; In fact, monokaryotic mycelium looks a lot like mold.&nbsp; <br />Once compatible hyphae 'mate' and become dikaryotic, (poly-nucleate) branching is much rarer and the mycelium begins to grow linearly.&nbsp; Rhizomorphic mycelium is simply hundreds or even thousands of strands of linear mycelium coiled into 'ropes'.&nbsp; With a good magnifying glass, you can see the individual strands.<br />It will be a week or so at least before one sees rhizomorphic mycelium in a jar, and even then it's rare.&nbsp; Usually it indicates a dry spawn or brf mix.<br />You were both wrong because they definitely don't form rhizomorphs on the day of germination, nor do they from day 6 or any other random number thereafter.<br />RR"}}